******
[3] UK: westward spread
Date: Fri 25 Mar 2011
Source: Farmers Guardian [edited]
http://www.farmersguardian.com/home/arable/arable-news/yellow-rust-spreads-west/37879.article


Yellow rust spreads west
------------------------
Yellow rust is now attacking winter wheat crops in both the east and
west of the country, says Syngenta.

The disease has been present in some crops since a least early
February [2011], according to a yellow rust monitoring service being
run on the Syngenta website at
http://www.syngenta-crop.co.uk/rust-by-region.aspx.

Until recently it seemed mainly confined to eastern counties and the
south Midlands. Now the disease has been identified as far west as
Shropshire and Herefordshire.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Stripe rust (also called yellow rust) of cereals is caused by the
fungus _Puccinia striiformis_ var. _striiformis_. The disease affects
wheat, some barley varieties, triticale, and a number of wild grasses.
It causes yellow leaf stripes and stunting of plants with yield losses
of 40 to 100 per cent.

Spores are wind dispersed in several cycles during the cropping
season, and the fungus survives on living host plants generating a
"green bridge" between seasons. Disease management includes the use of
resistant varieties, fungicide applications, and control of volunteer
crops.

New stripe rust strains with increased virulence are emerging
worldwide. Monitoring and resistance breeding programmes have been
established in different wheat growing regions.

In India, the emergence of a new strain was confirmed in Punjab and
Himachal Pradesh in 2009, and a change of wheat cultivars was
recommended to farmers (ProMED-mail post 20090329.1216). In the UK,
the Claire strain was recently reported for the 1st time (ProMED-mail
post 20110304.0705), and this strain is now considered a threat to
Europe.

